[src:mo-query-ordering/amortized-analysis] In computer science, **amortized analysis** is a method for analyzing a given algorithm's complexity, or how much of a resource, especially time or memory, it takes to execute.
[src:mo-query-ordering/amortized-analysis] The motivation for amortized analysis is that looking at the worst-case run time can be too pessimistic.
[src:mo-query-ordering/amortized-analysis] Instead, amortized analysis averages the running times of operations in a sequence over that sequence.
[src:mo-query-ordering/amortized-analysis] For a given operation of an algorithm, certain situations (e.g., input parametrizations or data structure contents) may imply a significant cost in resources, whereas other situations may not be as costly.
[src:mo-query-ordering/amortized-analysis] The amortized analysis considers both the costly and less costly operations together over the whole sequence of operations.
[src:mo-query-ordering/amortized-analysis] This may include accounting for different types of input, length of the input, and other factors that affect its performance.
[src:mo-query-ordering/amortized-analysis] Amortized analysis initially emerged from a method called aggregate analysis, which is now subsumed by amortized analysis.
[src:mo-query-ordering/amortized-analysis] The technique was first formally introduced by Robert Tarjan in his 1985 paper *Amortized Computational Complexity*, which addressed the need for a more useful form of analysis than the common probabilistic methods used.
[src:mo-query-ordering/amortized-analysis] Amortization was initially used for very specific types of algorithms, particularly those involving binary trees and union operations.
[src:mo-query-ordering/amortized-analysis] However, it is now ubiquitous and comes into play when analyzing many other algorithms as well.
[src:mo-query-ordering/amortized-analysis] Amortized analysis requires knowledge of which series of operations are possible.
[src:mo-query-ordering/amortized-analysis] This is most commonly the case with data structures, which have a state that persists between operations.
[src:mo-query-ordering/amortized-analysis] The basic idea is that a worst-case operation can alter the state in such a way that the worst case cannot occur again for a long time, thus "amortizing" its cost.
[src:mo-query-ordering/amortized-analysis] There are generally three methods for performing amortized analysis: the aggregate method, the accounting method, and the potential method.
[src:mo-query-ordering/amortized-analysis] All of these give correct answers; the choice of which to use depends on which is most convenient for a particular situation.
[src:mo-query-ordering/amortized-analysis] Consider a dynamic array that grows in size as more elements are added to it, such as `ArrayList` in Java or `std::vector` in C++.
[src:mo-query-ordering/amortized-analysis] If we started out with a dynamic array of size 4, we could push 4 elements onto it, and each operation would take constant time.
[src:mo-query-ordering/amortized-analysis] Yet pushing a fifth element onto that array would take longer as the array would have to create a new array of a scaled size, copy the old elements onto the new array, then add the new element.
[src:mo-query-ordering/amortized-analysis] The next few push operations would similarly take constant time, then the subsequent addition would require another slow scaling of the array size.
[src:mo-query-ordering/amortized-analysis] In general, for an arbitrary number n of pushes to an array of any initial size, the times for steps that scale the array add in a geometric series to $O(n)$ , while the constant times for each remaining push also add to $O(n)$ .
[src:mo-query-ordering/amortized-analysis] Therefore the average time per push operation is $O(n)/n=O(1)$ .
[src:mo-query-ordering/amortized-analysis] This reasoning can be formalized and generalized to more complicated data structures using amortized analysis.
[src:mo-query-ordering/amortized-analysis] The enqueue operation just pushes an element onto the input array; this operation does not depend on the lengths of either input or output and therefore runs in constant time.
[src:mo-query-ordering/amortized-analysis] However the dequeue operation is more complicated.
[src:mo-query-ordering/amortized-analysis] If the output array already has some elements in it, then dequeue runs in constant time; otherwise, dequeue takes ⁠ $O(n)$ ⁠ time to add all the elements onto the output array from the input array, where *n* is the current length of the input array.
[src:mo-query-ordering/amortized-analysis] After copying *n* elements from input, we can perform *n* dequeue operations, each taking constant time, before the output array is empty again.
[src:mo-query-ordering/amortized-analysis] Thus, we can perform a sequence of *n* dequeue operations in only ⁠ $O(n)$ ⁠ time, which implies that the amortized time of each dequeue operation is ⁠ $O(1)$ ⁠.
[src:mo-query-ordering/amortized-analysis] Alternatively, we can charge the cost of copying any item from the input array to the output array to the earlier enqueue operation for that item.
[src:mo-query-ordering/amortized-analysis] This charging scheme doubles the amortized time for enqueue but reduces the amortized time for dequeue to ⁠ $O(1)$ ⁠.
[src:mo-query-ordering/hilbert-curve] The **Hilbert curve** (also known as the **Hilbert space-filling curve**) is a continuous fractal space-filling curve first described by the German mathematician David Hilbert in 1891, as a variant of the space-filling Peano curves discovered by Giuseppe Peano in 1890.
[src:mo-query-ordering/hilbert-curve] Because it is space-filling, its Hausdorff dimension is 2 (precisely, its image is the unit square, whose dimension is 2 in any definition of dimension; its graph is a compact set homeomorphic to the closed unit interval, with Hausdorff dimension 1).
[src:mo-query-ordering/hilbert-curve] The Hilbert curve is constructed as a limit of piecewise linear curves.
[src:mo-query-ordering/hilbert-curve] The length of the n th curve is $\textstyle 2^{n}-{1 \over 2^{n}}$ , i.e., the length grows exponentially with n , even though each curve is contained in a square with area 1 .
[src:mo-query-ordering/hilbert-curve] Both the true Hilbert curve and its discrete approximations are useful because they give a mapping between 1D and 2D space that preserves locality fairly well.
[src:mo-query-ordering/hilbert-curve] This means that two data points which are close to each other in one-dimensional space are also close to each other after folding.
[src:mo-query-ordering/hilbert-curve] Because of this locality property, the Hilbert curve is widely used in computer science.
[src:mo-query-ordering/hilbert-curve] For example, the range of IP addresses used by computers can be mapped into a picture using the Hilbert curve.
[src:mo-query-ordering/hilbert-curve] Code to generate the image would map from 2D to 1D to find the color of each pixel, and the Hilbert curve is sometimes used because it keeps nearby IP addresses close to each other in the picture.
[src:mo-query-ordering/hilbert-curve] The locality property of the Hilbert curve has also been used to design algorithms for exploring regions with mobile robots and indexing geospatial location data.
[src:mo-query-ordering/hilbert-curve] In an algorithm called Riemersma dithering, grayscale photographs can be converted to a dithered black-and-white image using thresholding, with the leftover amount from each pixel added to the next pixel along the Hilbert curve.
[src:mo-query-ordering/hilbert-curve] Code to do this would map from 1D to 2D, and the Hilbert curve is sometimes used because it does not create the distracting patterns that would be visible to the eye if the order were simply left to right across each row of pixels.
[src:mo-query-ordering/hilbert-curve] Hilbert curves in higher dimensions are an instance of a generalization of Gray codes, and are sometimes used for similar purposes, for similar reasons.
[src:mo-query-ordering/hilbert-curve] For multidimensional databases, Hilbert order has been proposed to be used instead of Z order because it has better locality-preserving behavior.
[src:mo-query-ordering/hilbert-curve] For example, Hilbert curves have been used to compress and accelerate R-tree indexes (see Hilbert R-tree).
[src:mo-query-ordering/hilbert-curve] They have also been used to help compress data warehouses.
[src:mo-query-ordering/hilbert-curve] The linear distance of any point along the curve can be converted to coordinates in *n* dimensions for a given *n*, and vice versa, using any of several standard mathematical techniques such as Skilling's method.
[src:mo-query-ordering/hilbert-curve] It is possible to implement Hilbert curves efficiently even when the data space does not form a square.
[src:mo-query-ordering/hilbert-curve] Moreover, there are several possible generalizations of Hilbert curves to higher dimensions.
[src:mo-query-ordering/hilbert-curve] The Hilbert Curve can be expressed by a rewrite system (L-system).
[src:mo-query-ordering/hilbert-curve] Here, "F" means "draw forward", "+" means "turn left 90°", "-" means "turn right 90°" (see turtle graphics), and "A" and "B" are ignored during drawing.
[src:mo-query-ordering/hilbert-curve] The Hilbert Curve is commonly used among rendering images or videos.
[src:mo-query-ordering/hilbert-curve] Common programs such as Blender and Cinema 4D use the Hilbert Curve to trace the objects, and render the scene.
[src:mo-query-ordering/hilbert-curve] The slicer software used to convert 3D models into toolpaths for a 3D printer typically has the Hilbert curve as an option for an infill pattern.
[src:mo-query-ordering/query-optimization] Generally, the query optimizer cannot be accessed directly by users: once queries are submitted to the database server, and parsed by the parser, they are then passed to the query optimizer where optimization occurs.
[src:mo-query-ordering/query-optimization] However, some database engines allow guiding the query optimizer with hints.
[src:mo-query-ordering/query-optimization] A query is a request for information from a database.
[src:mo-query-ordering/query-optimization] Since database structures are complex, in most cases, and especially for not-very-simple queries, the needed data for a query can be collected from a database by accessing it in different ways, through different data-structures, and in different orders.
[src:mo-query-ordering/query-optimization] Each different way typically requires different processing time.
[src:mo-query-ordering/query-optimization] Processing times of the same query may have large variance, from a fraction of a second to hours, depending on the chosen method.
[src:mo-query-ordering/query-optimization] The purpose of query optimization, which is an automated process, is to find the way to process a given query in minimum time.
[src:mo-query-ordering/query-optimization] The large possible variance in time justifies performing query optimization, though finding the exact optimal query plan, among all possibilities, is typically very complex, time-consuming by itself, may be too costly, and often practically impossible.
[src:mo-query-ordering/query-optimization] Thus query optimization typically tries to approximate the optimum by comparing several common-sense alternatives to provide in a reasonable time a "good enough" plan which typically does not deviate much from the best possible result.
[src:mo-query-ordering/query-optimization] There is a trade-off between the amount of time spent figuring out the best query plan and the quality of the choice; the optimizer may not choose the best answer on its own.
[src:mo-query-ordering/query-optimization] Different qualities of database management systems have different ways of balancing these two.
[src:mo-query-ordering/query-optimization] Cost-based query optimizers evaluate the resource footprint of various query plans and use this as the basis for plan selection.
[src:mo-query-ordering/query-optimization] These assign an estimated "cost" to each possible query plan, and choose the plan with the smallest cost.
[src:mo-query-ordering/query-optimization] Costs are used to estimate the runtime cost of evaluating the query, in terms of the number of I/O operations required, CPU path length, amount of disk buffer space, disk storage service time, and interconnect usage between units of parallelism, and other factors determined from the data dictionary.
[src:mo-query-ordering/query-optimization] The set of query plans examined is formed by examining the possible access paths (e.g., primary index access, secondary index access, full file scan) and various relational table join techniques (e.g., merge join, hash join, product join).
[src:mo-query-ordering/query-optimization] The search space can become quite large depending on the complexity of the SQL query.
[src:mo-query-ordering/query-optimization] These consist of logical optimization—which generates a sequence of relational algebra to solve the query—and physical optimization—which is used to determine the means of carrying out each operation.
[src:mo-query-ordering/query-optimization] Most query optimizers represent query plans as a tree of "plan nodes".
[src:mo-query-ordering/query-optimization] A plan node encapsulates a single operation that is required to execute the query.
[src:mo-query-ordering/query-optimization] The nodes are arranged as a tree, in which intermediate results flow from the bottom of the tree to the top.
[src:mo-query-ordering/query-optimization] Each node has zero or more child nodes—those are nodes whose output is fed as input to the parent node.
[src:mo-query-ordering/query-optimization] For example, a join node will have two child nodes, which represent the two join operands, whereas a sort node would have a single child node (the input to be sorted).
[src:mo-query-ordering/query-optimization] The leaves of the tree are nodes which produce results by scanning the disk, for example by performing an index scan or a sequential scan.
[src:mo-query-ordering/query-optimization] The performance of a query plan is determined largely by the order in which the tables are joined.
[src:mo-query-ordering/query-optimization] For example, when joining 3 tables A, B, C of size 10 rows, 10,000 rows, and 1,000,000 rows, respectively, a query plan that joins B and C first can take several orders-of-magnitude more time to execute than one that joins A and C first.
[src:mo-query-ordering/query-optimization] Most query optimizers determine join order via a dynamic programming algorithm pioneered by IBM's System R database project .
[src:mo-query-ordering/query-optimization] The optimizer then considers combining each pair of relations for which a join condition exists.
[src:mo-query-ordering/query-optimization] For each pair, the optimizer will consider the available join algorithms implemented by the DBMS.
[src:mo-query-ordering/query-optimization] It will preserve the cheapest way to join each pair of relations, in addition to the cheapest way to join each pair of relations that produces its output according to a particular sort order.
[src:mo-query-ordering/query-optimization] Then all three-relation query plans are computed, by joining each two-relation plan produced by the previous phase with the remaining relations in the query.
[src:mo-query-ordering/query-optimization] Sort order can avoid a redundant sort operation later on in processing the query.
[src:mo-query-ordering/query-optimization] Second, a particular sort order can speed up a subsequent join because it clusters the data in a particular way.
[src:mo-query-ordering/query-optimization] A SQL query to a modern relational DBMS does more than just selections and joins.
[src:mo-query-ordering/query-optimization] In particular, SQL queries often nest several layers of SPJ blocks (Select-Project-Join), by means of group by, exists, and not exists operators.
[src:mo-query-ordering/query-optimization] In some cases such nested SQL queries can be flattened into a select-project-join query, but not always.
[src:mo-query-ordering/query-optimization] Query plans for nested SQL queries can also be chosen using the same dynamic programming algorithm as used for join ordering, but this can lead to an enormous escalation in query optimization time.
[src:mo-query-ordering/query-optimization] So some database management systems use an alternative rule-based approach that uses a query graph model.
[src:mo-query-ordering/query-optimization] One of the hardest problems in query optimization is to accurately estimate the costs of alternative query plans.
[src:mo-query-ordering/query-optimization] Optimizers cost query plans using a mathematical model of query execution costs that relies heavily on estimates of the cardinality, or number of tuples, flowing through each edge in a query plan.
[src:mo-query-ordering/query-optimization] Cardinality estimation in turn depends on estimates of the selection factor of predicates in the query.
[src:mo-query-ordering/query-optimization] Traditionally, database systems estimate selectivities through fairly detailed statistics on the distribution of values in each column, such as histograms.
[src:mo-query-ordering/query-optimization] This technique works well for estimation of selectivities of individual predicates.
[src:mo-query-ordering/query-optimization] However many queries have conjunctions of predicates such as `select count(*) from R where R.make='Honda' and R.model='Accord'`.
[src:mo-query-ordering/query-optimization] Query predicates are often highly correlated (for example, `model='Accord'` implies `make='Honda'`), and it is very hard to estimate the selectivity of the conjunct in general.
[src:mo-query-ordering/query-optimization] Poor cardinality estimates and uncaught correlation are one of the main reasons why query optimizers pick poor query plans.
[src:mo-query-ordering/query-optimization] This is one reason why a database administrator should regularly update the database statistics, especially after major data loads/unloads.
[src:mo-query-ordering/query-optimization] Classical query optimization assumes that query plans are compared according to one single cost metric, usually execution time, and that the cost of each query plan can be calculated without uncertainty.
[src:mo-query-ordering/query-optimization] Both assumptions are sometimes violated in practice and multiple extensions of classical query optimization have been studied in the research literature that overcome those limitations.
[src:mo-query-ordering/query-optimization] Those extended problem variants differ in how they model the cost of single query plans and in terms of their optimization goal.
[src:mo-query-ordering/query-optimization] Classical query optimization associates each query plan with one scalar cost value.
[src:mo-query-ordering/query-optimization] Parametric query optimization assumes that query plan cost depends on parameters whose values are unknown at optimization time.
[src:mo-query-ordering/query-optimization] Such parameters can for instance represent the selectivity of query predicates that are not fully specified at optimization time but will be provided at execution time.
[src:mo-query-ordering/query-optimization] Parametric query optimization therefore associates each query plan with a cost function that maps from a multi-dimensional parameter space to a one-dimensional cost space.
[src:mo-query-ordering/query-optimization] The goal of optimization is usually to generate all query plans that could be optimal for any of the possible parameter value combinations.
[src:mo-query-ordering/query-optimization] This yields a set of relevant query plans.
[src:mo-query-ordering/query-optimization] At run time, the best plan is selected out of that set once the true parameter values become known.
[src:mo-query-ordering/query-optimization] The advantage of parametric query optimization is that optimization (which is in general a very expensive operation) is avoided at run time.
[src:mo-query-ordering/query-optimization] There are often other cost metrics in addition to execution time that are relevant to compare query plans.
[src:mo-query-ordering/query-optimization] In a cloud computing scenario for instance, one should compare query plans not only in terms of how much time they take to execute but also in terms of how much money their execution costs.
[src:mo-query-ordering/query-optimization] Or in the context of approximate query optimization, it is possible to execute query plans on randomly selected samples of the input data in order to obtain approximate results with reduced execution overhead.
[src:mo-query-ordering/query-optimization] In such cases, alternative query plans must be compared in terms of their execution time but also in terms of the precision or reliability of the data they generate.
[src:mo-query-ordering/query-optimization] Multi-objective query optimization models the cost of a query plan as a cost vector where each vector component represents cost according to a different cost metric.
[src:mo-query-ordering/query-optimization] Classical query optimization can be considered as a special case of multi-objective query optimization where the dimension of the cost space (i.e., the number of cost vector components) is one.
[src:mo-query-ordering/query-optimization] Different cost metrics might conflict with each other (e.g., there might be one plan with minimal execution time and a different plan with minimal monetary execution fees in a cloud computing scenario).
[src:mo-query-ordering/query-optimization] Therefore, the goal of optimization cannot be to find a query plan that minimizes all cost metrics but must be to find a query plan that realizes the best compromise between different cost metrics.
[src:mo-query-ordering/query-optimization] What the best compromise is depends on user preferences (e.g., some users might prefer a cheaper plan while others prefer a faster plan in a cloud scenario).
[src:mo-query-ordering/query-optimization] Multi-objective parametric query optimization generalizes parametric and multi-objective query optimization.
[src:mo-query-ordering/query-optimization] Plans are compared according to multiple cost metrics and plan costs may depend on parameters whose values are unknown at optimization time.
[src:mo-query-ordering/query-optimization] The cost of a query plan is therefore modeled as a function from a multi-dimensional parameter space to a multi-dimensional cost space.
[src:mo-query-ordering/query-optimization] The goal of optimization is to generate the set of query plans that can be optimal for each possible combination of parameter values and user preferences.
[src:mo-query-ordering/query-optimization] A number of tools display query execution plans to show which operations have the highest processing cost.
[src:mo-query-ordering/query-optimization] Microsoft SMS, ApexSQLPlan, Hana, and Tableau are some examples.
[src:mo-query-ordering/query-optimization] Fixing these issues found in these plans can shave tens of percent execution time, and in some cases can cut two-dimensional searches to linear ones.
[src:mo-query-ordering/query-optimization] One of the primary and simplest optimization checklists is to use operations that most RDMS are designed to execute efficiently.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] In computer science, the **range query** problem consists of efficiently answering several queries regarding a given interval of elements within an array.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] For example, a common task, known as range minimum query, is finding the smallest value inside a given range within a list of numbers.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] Given a function f that accepts an array, a range query $f_{q}(l,r)$ on an array $a=[a_{1},..,a_{n}]$ takes two indices l and r and returns the result of f when applied to the subarray $[a_{l},\ldots ,a_{r}]$ .
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] For example, for a function $\operatorname {sum}$ that returns the sum of all values in an array, the range query $\operatorname {sum} _{q}(l,r)$ returns the sum of all values in the range $[l,r]$ .
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] Range sum queries may be answered in constant time and linear space by pre-computing an array p of same length as the input such that for every index i, the element pi is the sum of the first i elements of a.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] This strategy may be extended to any other binary operation f whose inverse function $f^{-1}$ is well-defined and easily computable.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] It can also be extended to higher dimensions with a similar pre-processing.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] A more difficult subset of the problem consists of executing range queries on dynamic data; that is, data that may mutate between each query.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] In order to efficiently update array values, more sophisticated data structures like the segment tree or Fenwick tree are necessary.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] When the function of interest in a range query is a semigroup operator, the notion of $f^{-1}$ is not always defined, so the strategy in the previous section does not work.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] Andrew Yao showed that there exists an efficient solution for range queries that involve semigroup operators.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] He proved that for any constant c, a pre-processing of time and space $\Theta (c\cdot n)$ allows to answer range queries on lists where f is a semigroup operator in $\theta (\alpha _{c}(n))$ time, where $\alpha _{c}$ is a certain functional inverse of the Ackermann function.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] There are some semigroup operators that admit slightly better solutions.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] For instance when $f\in \{\max ,\min \}$ .
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] Assume $f=\min$ then $\min(A[1..n])$ returns the index of the minimum element of $A[1..n]$ .
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] Then ${\textstyle \min _{i,j}(A)}$ denotes the corresponding minimum range query.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] There are several data structures that allow to answer a range minimum query in $O(1)$ time using a pre-processing of time and space $O(n)$ .
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] One such solution is based on the equivalence between this problem and the lowest common ancestor problem.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] The Cartesian tree $T_{A}$ of an array $A[1,n]$ has as root $a_{i}=\min\{a_{1},a_{2},\ldots ,a_{n}\}$ and as left and right subtrees the Cartesian tree of $A[1,i-1]$ and the Cartesian tree of $A[i+1,n]$ respectively.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] A range minimum query ${\textstyle \min _{i,j}(A)}$ is the lowest common ancestor in $T_{A}$ of $a_{i}$ and $a_{j}$ .
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] Because the lowest common ancestor can be solved in constant time using a pre-processing of time and space $O(n)$ , range minimum query can as well.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] The solution when $f=\max$ is analogous.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] Cartesian trees can be constructed in linear time.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] The mode of an array is the element that appears the most in it.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] In case of a tie, any of the most frequent elements might be picked as the mode.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] A range mode query consists in pre-processing $A[1,n]$ such that we can find the mode in any range of $A[1,n]$ .
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] Several data structures have been devised to solve this problem, we summarize some of the results in the following table.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] Recently Jørgensen et al. proved a lower bound on the cell-probe model of $\Omega \left({\tfrac {\log n}{\log(Sw/n)}}\right)$ for any data structure that uses S cells.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] This particular case is of special interest since finding the median has several applications.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] On the other hand, the median problem, a special case of the selection problem, is solvable in *O*(*n*), using the median of medians algorithm.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] However its generalization through range median queries is recent.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] A range median query $\operatorname {median} (A,i,j)$ where *A,i* and *j* have the usual meanings returns the median element of $A[i,j]$ .
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] Equivalently, $\operatorname {median} (A,i,j)$ should return the element of $A[i,j]$ of rank ${\frac {j-i}{2}}$ .
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] Range median queries cannot be solved by following any of the previous methods discussed above including Yao's approach for semigroup operators.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] There have been studied two variants of this problem, the offline version, where all the *k* queries of interest are given in a batch, and a version where all the pre-processing is done up front.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] The offline version can be solved with $O(n\log k+k\log n)$ time and $O(n\log k)$ space.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] The following pseudocode of the quickselect algorithm shows how to find the element of rank r in $A[i,j]$ an unsorted array of distinct elements, to find the range medians we set $r={\frac {j-i}{2}}$ .
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] Procedure `rangeMedian` partitions `A`, using `A`'s median, into two arrays `A.low` and `A.high`, where the former contains the elements of `A` that are less than or equal to the median `m` and the latter the rest of the elements of `A`.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] If we know that the number of elements of $A[i,j]$ that end up in `A.low` is `t` and this number is bigger than `r` then we should keep looking for the element of rank `r` in `A.low`; otherwise we should look for the element of rank $(r-t)$ in `A.high`.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] To find t, it is enough to find the maximum index $m\leq i-1$ such that $a_{m}$ is in `A.low` and the maximum index $l\leq j$ such that $a_{l}$ is in `A.high`.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] The total cost for any query, without considering the partitioning part, is $\log n$ since at most $\log n$ recursion calls are done and only a constant number of operations are performed in each of them (to get the value of t fractional cascading should be used).
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] If a linear algorithm to find the medians is used, the total cost of pre-processing for k range median queries is $n\log k$ .
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] The algorithm can also be modified to solve the online version of the problem.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] Finding frequent elements in a given set of items is one of the most important tasks in data mining.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] Finding frequent elements might be a difficult task to achieve when most items have similar frequencies.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] Therefore, it might be more beneficial if some threshold of significance was used for detecting such items.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] One of the most famous algorithms for finding the majority of an array was proposed by Boyer and Moore which is also known as the Boyer–Moore majority vote algorithm.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] Boyer and Moore proposed an algorithm to find the majority element of a string (if it has one) in $O(n)$ time and using $O(1)$ space.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] In the context of Boyer and Moore's work and generally speaking, a majority element in a set of items (for example string or an array) is one whose number of instances is more than half of the size of that set.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] Few years later, Misra and Gries proposed a more general version of Boyer and Moore's algorithm using $O\left(n\log \left({\frac {1}{\tau }}\right)\right)$ comparisons to find all items in an array whose relative frequencies are greater than some threshold $0<\tau <1$ .
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] A range $\tau$ -majority query is one that, given a subrange of a data structure (for example an array) of size $|R|$ , returns the set of all distinct items that appear more than (or in some publications equal to) $\tau |R|$ times in that given range.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] In different structures that support range $\tau$ -majority queries, $\tau$ can be either static (specified during pre-processing) or dynamic (specified at query time).
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] Many of such approaches are based on the fact that, regardless of the size of the range, for a given $\tau$ there could be at most $O(1/\tau )$ distinct *candidates* with relative frequencies at least $\tau$ .
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] By verifying each of these candidates in constant time, $O(1/\tau )$ query time is achieved.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] A range $\tau$ -majority query is decomposable in the sense that a $\tau$ -majority in a range R with partitions $R_{1}$ and $R_{2}$ must be a $\tau$ -majority in either $R_{1}$ or $R_{2}$ .
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] Gagie et al. proposed a data structure that supports range $\tau$ -majority queries on an $m\times n$ array A .
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] This data structure supports dynamic thresholds (specified at query time) and a pre-processing threshold $\alpha$ based on which it is constructed.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] During the pre-processing, a set of *vertical* and *horizontal* intervals are built on the $m\times n$ array.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] Together, a vertical and a horizontal interval form a *block.* Each block is part of a *superblock* nine times bigger than itself (three times the size of the block's horizontal interval and three times the size of its vertical one).
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] For each block a set of candidates (with ${\frac {9}{\alpha }}$ elements at most) is stored which consists of elements that have relative frequencies at least ${\frac {\alpha }{9}}$ (the pre-processing threshold as mentioned above) in its respective superblock.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] These elements are stored in non-increasing order according to their frequencies and it is easy to see that, any element that has a relative frequency at least $\alpha$ in a block must appear its set of candidates.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] Each $\tau$ -majority query is first answered by finding the *query block,* or the biggest block that is contained in the provided query rectangle in $O(1)$ time.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] For the obtained query block, the first ${\frac {9}{\tau }}$ candidates are returned (without being verified) in $O(1/\tau )$ time, so this process might return some false positives.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] Many other data structures (as discussed below) have proposed methods for verifying each candidate in constant time and thus maintaining the $O(1/\tau )$ query time while returning no false positives.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] where $\beta$ is the pre-processing threshold of the i -th instance.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] Thus, for query blocks smaller than $1/\alpha$ the $\lceil \log(1/\tau )\rceil$ -th instance is queried.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] As mentioned above, this data structure has query time $O(1/\tau )$ and requires $O\left(mn(H+1)\log ^{2}\left({\frac {1}{\alpha }}\right)\right)$ bits of space by storing a Huffman-encoded copy of it (note the $\log({\frac {1}{\alpha }})$ factor and also see Huffman coding).
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] Chan et al. proposed a data structure that given a one-dimensional array A , a subrange R of A (specified at query time) and a threshold $\tau$ (specified at query time), is able to return the list of all $\tau$ -majorities in $O(1/\tau )$ time requiring $O(n\log n)$ words of space.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] To answer such queries, Chan et al. begin by noting that there exists a data structure capable of returning the *top-k* most frequent items in a range in $O(k)$ time requiring $O(n)$ words of space.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] For a one-dimensional array $A[0,..,n-1]$ , let a one-sided top-k range query to be of form $A[0..i]{\text{ for }}0\leq i\leq n-1$ .
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] For a maximal range of ranges $A[0..i]{\text{ through }}A[0..j]$ in which the frequency of a distinct element e in A remains unchanged (and equal to f ), a horizontal line segment is constructed.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] The x -interval of this line segment corresponds to $[i,j]$ and it has a y -value equal to f .
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] Since adding each element to A changes the frequency of exactly one distinct element, the aforementioned process creates $O(n)$ line segments.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] Moreover, for a vertical line $x=i$ all horizontal line segments intersecting it are sorted according to their frequencies.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] Note that, each horizontal line segment with x -interval $[\ell ,r]$ corresponds to exactly one distinct element e in A , such that $A[\ell ]=e$ .
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] A top-k query can then be answered by shooting a vertical ray $x=i$ and reporting the first k horizontal line segments that intersect it (remember from above that these line segments are already sorted according to their frequencies) in $O(k)$ time.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] Chan et al. first construct a range tree in which each branching node stores one copy of the data structure described above for one-sided range top-k queries and each leaf represents an element from A .
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] The top-k data structure at each node is constructed based on the values existing in the subtrees of that node and is meant to answer one-sided range top-k queries.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] Please note that for a one-dimensional array A , a range tree can be constructed by dividing A into two halves and recursing on both halves; therefore, each node of the resulting range tree represents a range.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] It can also be seen that this range tree requires $O(n\log n)$ words of space, because there are $O(\log n)$ levels and each level $\ell$ has $2^{\ell }$ nodes.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] Moreover, since at each level $\ell$ of a range tree all nodes have a total of n elements of A at their subtrees and since there are $O(\log n)$ levels, the space complexity of this range tree is $O(n\log n)$ .
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] Using this structure, a range $\tau$ -majority query $A[i..j]$ on $A[0..n-1]$ with $0\leq i\leq j\leq n$ is answered as follows.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] First, the lowest common ancestor (LCA) of leaf nodes i and j is found in constant time.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] Note that there exists a data structure requiring $O(n)$ bits of space that is capable of answering the LCA queries in $O(1)$ time.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] Let z denote the LCA of i and j , using z and according to the decomposability of range $\tau$ -majority queries (as described above and in ), the two-sided range query $A[i..j]$ can be converted into two one-sided range top-k queries (from z to i and j ).
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] These two one-sided range top-k queries return the top-( $1/\tau$ ) most frequent elements in each of their respective ranges in $O(1/\tau )$ time.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] These frequent elements make up the set of *candidates* for $\tau$ -majorities in $A[i..j]$ in which there are $O(1/\tau )$ candidates some of which might be false positives.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] Each candidate is then assessed in constant time using a linear-space data structure (as described in Lemma 3 in ) that is able to determine in $O(1)$ time whether or not a given subrange of an array A contains at least q instances of a particular element e .
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] Gagie et al. proposed a data structure which supports queries such that, given two nodes u and v in a tree, are able to report the list of elements that have a greater relative frequency than $\tau$ on the path from u to v .
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] More formally, let T be a labelled tree in which each node has a label from an alphabet of size $\sigma$ .
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] Let $label(u)\in [1,\dots ,\sigma ]$ denote the label of node u in T .
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] Let $P_{uv}$ denote the unique path from u to v in T in which middle nodes are listed in the order they are visited.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] Given T , and a fixed (specified during pre-processing) threshold $0<\tau <1$ , a query $Q(u,v)$ must return the set of all labels that appear more than $\tau |P_{uv}|$ times in $P_{uv}$ .
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] To construct this data structure, first ${O}(\tau n)$ nodes are *marked*.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] This can be done by marking any node that has distance at least $\lceil 1/\tau \rceil$ from the bottom of the three (height) and whose depth is divisible by $\lceil 1/\tau \rceil$ .
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] After doing this, it can be observed that the distance between each node and its nearest marked ancestor is less than $2\lceil 1/\tau \rceil$ .
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] for $0\leq i\leq \log(depth(x))$ where $\operatorname {par} (x)$ returns the label of the direct parent of node x .
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] Put another way, for each marked node, the set of all paths with a power of two length (plus one for the node itself) towards the root is stored.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] Moreover, for each $P_{i}(x)$ , the set of all majority *candidates* $C_{i}(x)$ are stored.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] It is easy to see that the set of candidates $C_{i}(x)$ can have at most $2/\tau$ distinct labels for each i .
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] The existence of such $P_{i}(x)$ implies that a $\tau$ -majority in the path from x to z must be a $(\tau /2)$ -majority in $P_{i}(x)$ , and thus must appear in $C_{i}(x)$ .
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] It is easy to see that this data structure require $O(n\log n)$ words of space, because as mentioned above in the construction phase $O(\tau n)$ nodes are marked and for each marked node some candidate sets are stored.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] By definition, for each marked node $O(\log n)$ of such sets are stores, each of which contains $O(1/\tau )$ candidates.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] Therefore, this data structure requires $O(\log n\times (1/\tau )\times \tau n)=O(n\log n)$ words of space.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] Please note that each node x also stores $count(x)$ which is equal to the number of instances of $label(x)$ on the path from x to the root of T , this does not increase the space complexity since it only adds a constant number of words per node.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] Each query between two nodes u and v can be answered by using the decomposability property (as explained above) of range $\tau$ -majority queries and by breaking the query path between u and v into four subpaths.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] Let z be the lowest common ancestor of u and v , with x and y being the nearest marked ancestors of u and v respectively.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] Please note that, boundary nodes have to be handled accordingly so that all of these subpaths are disjoint and from all of them a set of $O(1/\tau )$ candidates is derived.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] Each of these candidates is then verified using a combination of the $labelanc(x,\ell )$ query which returns the lowest ancestor of node x that has label $\ell$ and the $count(x)$ fields of each node.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] On a w -bit RAM and an alphabet of size $\sigma$ , the $labelanc(x,\ell )$ query can be answered in $O\left(\log \log _{w}\sigma \right)$ time whilst having linear space requirements.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] Therefore, verifying each of the $O(1/\tau )$ candidates in $O\left(\log \log _{w}\sigma \right)$ time results in $O\left((1/\tau )\log \log _{w}\sigma \right)$ total query time for returning the set of all $\tau$ -majorities on the path from u to v .
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] All the problems described above have been studied for higher dimensions as well as their dynamic versions.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] On the other hand, range queries might be extended to other data structures like trees, such as the level ancestor problem.
[src:mo-query-ordering/range-query-data-structures] A similar family of problems are orthogonal range queries, also known as counting queries.
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] In computer science, a **selection algorithm** is an algorithm for finding the k th smallest value in a collection of orderable values, such as numbers.
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] The value that it finds is called the k th order statistic.
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] Selection includes as special cases the problems of finding the minimum, median, and maximum element in the collection.
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] Selection algorithms include quickselect, and the median of medians algorithm.
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] When applied to a collection of n values, these algorithms take linear time, $O(n)$ as expressed using big O notation.
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] For data that is already structured, faster algorithms may be possible; as an extreme case, selection in an already-sorted array takes time $O(1)$ .
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] An algorithm for the selection problem takes as input a collection of values, and a number k .
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] It outputs the k th smallest of these values, or, in some versions of the problem, a collection of the k smallest values.
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] For this to be well-defined, it should be possible to sort the values into an order from smallest to largest; for instance, they may be integers, floating-point numbers, or some other kind of object with a numeric key.
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] However, they are not assumed to have been already sorted.
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] To simplify the problem, some works on this problem assume that the values are all distinct from each other, or that some consistent tie-breaking method has been used to assign an ordering to pairs of items with the same value as each other.
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] This article follows the conventions used by Cormen et al., according to which all values are distinct and the minimum value is obtained from $k=1$ .
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] With these conventions, the maximum value, among a collection of n values, is obtained by setting $k=n$ .
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] When n is an odd number, the median of the collection is obtained by setting $k=(n+1)/2$ .
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] When n is even, there are two choices for the median, obtained by rounding this choice of k down or up, respectively: the *lower median* with $k=n/2$ and the *upper median* with $k=n/2+1$ .
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] The time for this method is dominated by the sorting step, which requires $\Theta (n\log n)$ time using a comparison sort.
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] Even when integer sorting algorithms may be used, these are generally slower than the linear time that may be achieved using specialized selection algorithms.
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] Nevertheless, the simplicity of this approach makes it attractive, especially when a highly-optimized sorting routine is provided as part of a runtime library, but a selection algorithm is not.
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] For inputs of moderate size, sorting can be faster than non-random selection algorithms, because of the smaller constant factors in its running time.
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] This method also produces a sorted version of the collection, which may be useful for other later computations, and in particular for selection with other choices of k .
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] For a sorting algorithm that generates one item at a time, such as selection sort, the scan can be done in tandem with the sort, and the sort can be terminated once the k th element has been found.
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] One possible design of a consolation bracket in a single-elimination tournament, in which the teams who lost to the eventual winner play another mini-tournament to determine second place, can be seen as an instance of this method.
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] Applying this optimization to heapsort produces the heapselect algorithm, which can select the k th smallest value in time $O(n+k\log n)$ .
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] This is fast when k is small relative to n , but degenerates to $O(n\log n)$ for larger values of k , such as the choice $k=n/2$ used for median finding.
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] Many methods for selection are based on choosing a special "pivot" element from the input, and using comparisons with this element to divide the remaining $n-1$ input values into two subsets: the set L of elements less than the pivot, and the set R of elements greater than the pivot.
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] The algorithm can then determine where the k th smallest value is to be found, based on a comparison of k with the sizes of these sets.
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] In particular, if $k\leq |L|$ , the k th smallest value is in L , and can be found recursively by applying the same selection algorithm to L .
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] If $k=|L|+1$ , then the k th smallest value is the pivot, and it can be returned immediately.
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] In the remaining case, the k th smallest value is in R , and more specifically it is the element in position $k-|L|-1$ of R .
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] It can be found by applying a selection algorithm recursively, seeking the value in this position in R .
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] As with the related pivoting-based quicksort algorithm, the partition of the input into L and R may be done by making new collections for these sets, or by a method that partitions a given list or array data type in-place.
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] Details vary depending on how the input collection is represented.
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] The time to compare the pivot against all the other values is $O(n)$ .
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] However, pivoting methods differ in how they choose the pivot, which affects how big the subproblems in each recursive call will be.
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] The efficiency of these methods depends greatly on the choice of the pivot.
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] If the pivot is chosen badly, the running time of this method can be as slow as $O(n^{2})$ .
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] The deterministic selection algorithms with the smallest known numbers of comparisons, for values of k that are far from 1 or n , are based on the concept of *factories*, introduced in 1976 by Arnold Schönhage, Mike Paterson, and Nick Pippenger.
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] These are methods that build partial orders of certain specified types, on small subsets of input values, by using comparisons to combine smaller partial orders.
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] As a very simple example, one type of factory can take as input a sequence of single-element partial orders, compare pairs of elements from these orders, and produce as output a sequence of two-element totally ordered sets.
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] The elements used as the inputs to this factory could either be input values that have not been compared with anything yet, or "waste" values produced by other factories.
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] A careful design of these factories leads to an algorithm that, when applied to median-finding, uses at most $2.942n$ comparisons.
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] For other values of k , the number of comparisons is smaller.
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] Researchers later found parallel algorithms for selection in $O(\log \log n)$ steps, matching this bound.
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] In a randomized parallel comparison tree model it is possible to perform selection in a bounded number of steps and a linear number of comparisons.
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] On the more realistic parallel RAM model of computing, with exclusive read exclusive write memory access, selection can be performed in time $O(\log n)$ with $O(n/\log n)$ processors, which is optimal both in time and in the number of processors.
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] With concurrent memory access, slightly faster parallel time is possible in general, and the $\log n$ term in the time bound can be replaced by $\log k$ .
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] When data is already organized into a data structure, it may be possible to perform selection in an amount of time that is sublinear in the number of values.
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] As a simple case of this, for data already sorted into an array, selecting the k th element may be performed by a single array lookup, in constant time.
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] For values organized into a two-dimensional array of size $m\times n$ , with sorted rows and columns, selection may be performed in time $O{\bigl (}m\log(2n/m){\bigr )}$ , or faster when k is small relative to the array dimensions.
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] For a collection of m one-dimensional sorted arrays, with $k_{i}$ items less than the selected item in the i th array, the time is ${\textstyle O{\bigl (}m+\sum _{i=1}^{m}\log(k_{i}+1){\bigr )}}$ .
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] Selection from data in a binary heap takes time $O(k)$ .
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] This is independent of the size n of the heap, and faster than the $O(k\log n)$ time bound that would be obtained from best-first search.
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] This same method can be applied more generally to data organized as any kind of heap-ordered tree (a tree in which each node stores one value in which the parent of each non-root node has a smaller value than its child).
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] In the other direction, linear time selection algorithms have been used as a subroutine in a priority queue data structure related to the heap, improving the time for extracting its k th item from $O(\log n)$ to $O(\log ^{*}n+\log k)$ ; here $\log ^{*}n$ is the iterated logarithm.
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] Going beyond the comparison model of computation, faster times per operation are possible for values that are small integers, on which binary arithmetic operations are allowed.
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] The $O(n)$ running time of the selection algorithms described above is necessary, because a selection algorithm that can handle inputs in an arbitrary order must take that much time to look at all of its inputs.
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] If any one of its input values is not compared, that one value could be the one that should have been selected, and the algorithm can be made to produce an incorrect answer.
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] Beyond this simple argument, there has been a significant amount of research on the exact number of comparisons needed for selection, both in the randomized and deterministic cases.
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] Selecting the minimum of n values requires $n-1$ comparisons, because the $n-1$ values that are not selected must each have been determined to be non-minimal, by being the largest in some comparison, and no two of these values can be largest in the same comparison.
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] The same argument applies symmetrically to selecting the maximum.
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] The next simplest case is selecting the second-smallest.
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] After several incorrect attempts, the first tight lower bound on this case was published in 1964 by Soviet mathematician Sergey Kislitsyn.
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] It can be shown by observing that selecting the second-smallest also requires distinguishing the smallest value from the rest, and by considering the number p of comparisons involving the smallest value that an algorithm for this problem makes.
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] Each of the p items that were compared to the smallest value is a candidate for second-smallest, and $p-1$ of these values must be found larger than another value in a second comparison in order to rule them out as second-smallest.
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] With $n-1$ values being the larger in at least one comparison, and $p-1$ values being the larger in at least two comparisons, there are a total of at least $n+p-2$ comparisons.
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] An adversary argument, in which the outcome of each comparison is chosen in order to maximize p (subject to consistency with at least one possible ordering) rather than by the numerical values of the given items, shows that it is possible to force p to be at least $\log _{2}n$ .
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] Therefore, the worst-case number of comparisons needed to select the second smallest is $n+\lceil \log _{2}n\rceil -2$ , the same number that would be obtained by holding a single-elimination tournament with a run-off tournament among the values that lost to the smallest value.
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] More generally, selecting the k th element out of n requires at least $n+\min(k,n-k)-O(1)$ comparisons, in the average case, matching the number of comparisons of the Floyd–Rivest algorithm up to its $o(n)$ term.
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] The argument is made directly for deterministic algorithms, with a number of comparisons that is averaged over all possible permutations of the input values.
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] By Yao's principle, it also applies to the expected number of comparisons for a randomized algorithm on its worst-case input.
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] For deterministic algorithms, it has been shown that selecting the k th element requires ${\bigl (}1+H(k/n){\bigr )}n+\Omega ({\sqrt {n}})$ comparisons, where $H(x)=x\log _{2}{\frac {1}{x}}+(1-x)\log _{2}{\frac {1}{1-x}}$ is the binary entropy function.
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] The special case of median-finding has a slightly larger lower bound on the number of comparisons, at least $(2+\varepsilon )n$ , for $\varepsilon \approx 2^{-80}$ .
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] Knuth supplies the following triangle of numbers summarizing pairs of n and k for which the exact number of comparisons needed by an optimal selection algorithm is known.
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] The n th row of the triangle (starting with $n=1$ in the top row) gives the numbers of comparisons for inputs of n values, and the k th number within each row gives the number of comparisons needed to select the k th smallest value from an input of that size.
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] The rows are symmetric because selecting the k th smallest requires exactly the same number of comparisons, in the worst case, as selecting the k th largest.
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] Some of the larger entries were proven to be optimal using a computer search.
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] Very few languages have built-in support for general selection, although many provide facilities for finding the smallest or largest element of a list.
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] Notable exceptions are the standard libraries of C++ and Rust.
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] The Standard Template Library of C++ provides a templated `nth_element` method with a guarantee of expected linear time.
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] Rust's standard library provides multiple variants of the `select_nth_unstable` member function for the `slice` data type.
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] These variants all have guaranteed linear running time for all inputs.
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] Python's standard library includes `heapq.nsmallest` and `heapq.nlargest` functions for returning the smallest or largest elements from a collection, in sorted order.
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] The implementation maintains a binary heap, limited to holding k elements, and initialized to the first k elements in the collection.
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] Then, each subsequent item of the collection may replace the largest or smallest element in the heap if it is smaller or larger than this element.
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] The algorithm's memory usage is superior to heapselect (the former only holds k elements in memory at a time while the latter requires manipulating the entire dataset into memory).
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] The best case is $O((n-k)+k\log k)$ for already sorted data.
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] The worst-case is $O(n\log k)$ for reverse sorted data.
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] In average cases, there are likely to be few heap updates and most input elements are processed with only a single comparison.
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] For example, extracting the 100 largest or smallest values out of 10,000,000 random inputs makes 10,009,401 comparisons on average.
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] Since 2017, Matlab has included `maxk()` and `mink()` functions, which return the maximal (minimal) k values in a vector as well as their indices.
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] The Matlab documentation does not specify which algorithm these functions use or what their running time is.
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] Quickselect was presented without analysis by Tony Hoare in 1965, and first analyzed in a 1971 technical report by Donald Knuth.
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] The first known linear time deterministic selection algorithm is the median of medians method, published in 1973 by Manuel Blum, Robert W.
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] Floyd, Vaughan Pratt, Ron Rivest, and Robert Tarjan.
[src:mo-query-ordering/selection-algorithm] They trace the formulation of the selection problem to work of Charles L.
[src:mo-query-ordering/space-filling-curve] In mathematical analysis, a **space-filling curve** is a curve whose range reaches every point in a higher dimensional region, typically the unit square (or more generally an *n*-dimensional unit hypercube).
[src:mo-query-ordering/space-filling-curve] Because Giuseppe Peano (1858–1932) was the first to discover one, space-filling curves in the 2-dimensional plane are sometimes called *Peano curves*, but that phrase also refers to the Peano curve, the specific example of a space-filling curve found by Peano.
[src:mo-query-ordering/space-filling-curve] The closely related **FASS curves** (FASS is an acronym for "approximately space-Filling, self-Avoiding, Simple, and Self-similar" curves) can be thought of as finite approximations of a certain type of space-filling curves.
[src:mo-query-ordering/space-filling-curve] Intuitively, a curve in two or three (or higher) dimensions can be thought of as the path of a continuously moving point.
[src:mo-query-ordering/space-filling-curve] In the most general form, the range of such a function may lie in an arbitrary topological space, but in the most commonly studied cases, the range will lie in a Euclidean space such as the 2-dimensional plane (a *planar curve*) or the 3-dimensional space (*space curve*).
[src:mo-query-ordering/space-filling-curve] Sometimes, the curve is identified with the image of the function (the set of all possible values of the function), instead of the function itself.
[src:mo-query-ordering/space-filling-curve] It is also possible to define curves without endpoints to be a continuous function on the real line (or on the open unit interval (0, 1)).
[src:mo-query-ordering/space-filling-curve] In 1890, Giuseppe Peano discovered a continuous curve, now called the Peano curve, that passes through every point of the unit square.
[src:mo-query-ordering/space-filling-curve] His purpose was to construct a continuous mapping from the unit interval onto the unit square.
[src:mo-query-ordering/space-filling-curve] Peano was motivated by Georg Cantor's earlier counterintuitive result that the infinite number of points in a unit interval is the same cardinality as the infinite number of points in any finite-dimensional manifold, such as the unit square.
[src:mo-query-ordering/space-filling-curve] The problem Peano solved was whether such a mapping could be continuous; i.e., a curve that fills a space.
[src:mo-query-ordering/space-filling-curve] Peano's solution does not set up a continuous one-to-one correspondence between the unit interval and the unit square, and indeed such a correspondence does not exist (see § Properties below).
[src:mo-query-ordering/space-filling-curve] It was common to associate the vague notions of *thinness* and 1-dimensionality to curves; all normally encountered curves were piecewise differentiable (that is, have piecewise continuous derivatives), and such curves cannot fill up the entire unit square.
[src:mo-query-ordering/space-filling-curve] Therefore, Peano's space-filling curve was found to be highly counterintuitive.
[src:mo-query-ordering/space-filling-curve] From Peano's example, it was easy to deduce continuous curves whose ranges contained the *n*-dimensional hypercube (for any positive integer *n*).
[src:mo-query-ordering/space-filling-curve] It was also easy to extend Peano's example to continuous curves without endpoints, which filled the entire *n*-dimensional Euclidean space (where *n* is 2, 3, or any other positive integer).
[src:mo-query-ordering/space-filling-curve] Most well-known space-filling curves are constructed iteratively as the limit of a sequence of piecewise linear continuous curves, each one more closely approximating the space-filling limit.
[src:mo-query-ordering/space-filling-curve] Peano's ground-breaking article contained no illustrations of his construction, which is defined in terms of ternary expansions and a mirroring operator.
[src:mo-query-ordering/space-filling-curve] But the graphical construction was perfectly clear to him—he made an ornamental tiling showing a picture of the curve in his home in Turin.
[src:mo-query-ordering/space-filling-curve] Peano's article also ends by observing that the technique can be obviously extended to other odd bases besides base 3.
[src:mo-query-ordering/space-filling-curve] His choice to avoid any appeal to graphical visualization was motivated by a desire for a completely rigorous proof owing nothing to pictures.
[src:mo-query-ordering/space-filling-curve] At that time (the beginning of the foundation of general topology), graphical arguments were still included in proofs, yet were becoming a hindrance to understanding often counterintuitive results.
[src:mo-query-ordering/space-filling-curve] A year later, David Hilbert published in the same journal a variation of Peano's construction.
[src:mo-query-ordering/space-filling-curve] Hilbert's article was the first to include a picture helping to visualize the construction technique, essentially the same as illustrated here.
[src:mo-query-ordering/space-filling-curve] The analytic form of the Hilbert curve, however, is more complicated than Peano's.
[src:mo-query-ordering/space-filling-curve] Let ${\mathcal {C}}$ denote the Cantor space $\mathbf {2} ^{\mathbb {N} }$ .
[src:mo-query-ordering/space-filling-curve] We start with a continuous function h from the Cantor space ${\mathcal {C}}$ onto the entire unit interval $[0,\,1]$ .
[src:mo-query-ordering/space-filling-curve] Since the Cantor set ${\mathcal {C}}$ is homeomorphic to its cartesian product with itself ${\mathcal {C}}\times {\mathcal {C}}$ , there is a continuous bijection g from the Cantor set onto ${\mathcal {C}}\;\times \;{\mathcal {C}}$ .
[src:mo-query-ordering/space-filling-curve] The composition f of H and g is a continuous function mapping the Cantor set onto the entire unit square.
[src:mo-query-ordering/space-filling-curve] Finally, one can extend f to a continuous function F whose domain is the entire unit interval $[0,\,1]$ .
[src:mo-query-ordering/space-filling-curve] If a curve is not injective, then one can find two intersecting *subcurves* of the curve, each obtained by considering the images of two disjoint segments from the curve's domain (the unit line segment).
[src:mo-query-ordering/space-filling-curve] The two subcurves intersect if the intersection of the two images is non-empty.
[src:mo-query-ordering/space-filling-curve] One might be tempted to think that the meaning of *curves intersecting* is that they necessarily cross each other, like the intersection point of two non-parallel lines, from one side to the other.
[src:mo-query-ordering/space-filling-curve] However, two curves (or two subcurves of one curve) may contact one another without crossing, as, for example, a line tangent to a circle does.
[src:mo-query-ordering/space-filling-curve] A non-self-intersecting continuous curve cannot fill the unit square because that will make the curve a homeomorphism from the unit interval onto the unit square (any continuous bijection from a compact space onto a Hausdorff space is a homeomorphism).
[src:mo-query-ordering/space-filling-curve] But a unit square has no cut-point, and so cannot be homeomorphic to the unit interval, in which all points except the endpoints are cut-points.
[src:mo-query-ordering/space-filling-curve] There exist non-self-intersecting curves of nonzero area, the Osgood curves, but by Netto's theorem they are not space-filling.
[src:mo-query-ordering/space-filling-curve] For the classic Peano and Hilbert space-filling curves, where two subcurves intersect (in the technical sense), there is self-contact without self-crossing.
[src:mo-query-ordering/space-filling-curve] A space-filling curve can be (everywhere) self-crossing if its approximation curves are self-crossing.
[src:mo-query-ordering/space-filling-curve] A space-filling curve's approximations can be self-avoiding, as the figures above illustrate.
[src:mo-query-ordering/space-filling-curve] In 3 dimensions, self-avoiding approximation curves can even contain knots.
[src:mo-query-ordering/space-filling-curve] Approximation curves remain within a bounded portion of *n*-dimensional space, but their lengths increase without bound.
[src:mo-query-ordering/space-filling-curve] Space-filling curves are special cases of fractal curves.
[src:mo-query-ordering/space-filling-curve] No differentiable space-filling curve can exist.
[src:mo-query-ordering/space-filling-curve] Roughly speaking, differentiability puts a bound on how fast the curve can turn.
[src:mo-query-ordering/space-filling-curve] Michał Morayne proved that the continuum hypothesis is equivalent to the existence of a Peano curve such that at each point of the real line at least one of its components is differentiable.
[src:mo-query-ordering/space-filling-curve] Spaces that are the continuous image of a unit interval are sometimes called *Peano spaces*.
[src:mo-query-ordering/space-filling-curve] In many formulations of the Hahn–Mazurkiewicz theorem, *second-countable* is replaced by *metrizable*.
[src:mo-query-ordering/space-filling-curve] In one direction a compact Hausdorff space is a normal space and, by Urysohn's metrization theorem, second-countable then implies metrizable.
[src:mo-query-ordering/space-filling-curve] Conversely, a compact metric space is second-countable.
[src:mo-query-ordering/space-filling-curve] There are many natural examples of space-filling, or rather sphere-filling, curves in the theory of doubly degenerate Kleinian groups.
[src:mo-query-ordering/space-filling-curve] For example, Cannon & Thurston (2007) showed that the circle at infinity of the universal cover of a fiber of a mapping torus of a pseudo-Anosov map is a sphere-filling curve.
[src:mo-query-ordering/space-filling-curve] Wiener pointed out in *The Fourier Integral and Certain of its Applications* that space-filling curves could be used to reduce Lebesgue integration in higher dimensions to Lebesgue integration in one dimension.
